Microbial classification is the process of classifying microorganisms into groups based on their characteristics. This is done to understand the diversity of microorganisms and to identify new species. There are several methods used for microbial classification, including morphological, biochemical, and molecular methods.
Morphological classification is based on the physical appearance of the microorganism, such as its shape, size, and color. This method is useful for identifying bacteria and fungi, but it is not very accurate for identifying viruses.
Biochemical classification is based on the metabolic activities of the microorganism, such as its ability to ferment sugars or produce certain enzymes. This method is more accurate than morphological classification, but it is not always reliable.
